01:20:31,880 --> 01:20:33,580
But that's not important to us.

2047
01:20:33,620 --> 01:20:34,920
Let's not fool around with that.

2048
01:20:34,980 --> 01:20:36,040
Let's just leave it as mg.

2049
01:20:37,220 --> 01:20:38,280
That's the temperature,

2050
01:20:38,400 --> 01:20:41,480
the change in entropy when you add one bit.

2051
01:20:41,940 --> 01:20:44,080
So this is an application of that idea,

2052
01:20:44,300 --> 01:20:47,260
and it's very interesting and unusual.

2053
01:20:48,140 --> 01:20:50,480
It's unusual because remember,

2054
01:20:50,640 --> 01:20:52,380
m is the energy of the black hole,

2055
01:20:52,480 --> 01:20:56,300
and the temperature decreases with energy.

2056
01:20:57,140 --> 01:20:59,680
So this is a very unusual situation

2057
01:20:59,680 --> 01:21:02,940
where a system's energy...

2058
01:21:04,760 --> 01:21:05,460
sorry,

2059
01:21:05,460 --> 01:21:07,540
where a system's temperature

2060
01:21:07,540 --> 01:21:10,300
is inverse to its energy.

2061
01:21:10,600 --> 01:21:12,360
How many systems have you ever heard of

2062
01:21:12,360 --> 01:21:15,620
whose temperature increases

2063
01:21:16,480 --> 01:21:18,620
when the mass decreases?

2064
01:21:19,680 --> 01:21:21,540
Or when the energy...

2065
01:21:21,540 --> 01:21:22,840
whose temperature increases

2066
01:21:22,840 --> 01:21:24,820
when the energy decreases?

2067
01:21:27,900 --> 01:21:29,700
Anybody know a system that does that,

2068
01:21:29,760 --> 01:21:30,920
other than a black hole?

2069
01:21:33,020 --> 01:21:33,440
Okay,

2070
01:21:33,440 --> 01:21:33,880
I'll tell you.

2071
01:21:33,960 --> 01:21:35,460
They're actually extremely common.

2072
01:21:39,320 --> 01:21:39,740
No,

2073
01:21:39,740 --> 01:21:39,980
no,

2074
01:21:39,980 --> 01:21:40,140
no,

2075
01:21:40,140 --> 01:21:40,300
no,

2076
01:21:40,300 --> 01:21:40,420
no,

2077
01:21:40,420 --> 01:21:40,460
no.

2078
01:21:40,460 --> 01:21:41,360
They're not that common.

2079
01:21:43,860 --> 01:21:44,660
A star.

2080
01:21:45,560 --> 01:21:46,180
A star.

2081
01:21:46,260 --> 01:21:47,280
What happens to a star

2082
01:21:47,280 --> 01:21:48,300
when it runs out of fuel?

2083
01:21:53,059 --> 01:21:53,620
It's a gas.

2084
01:21:53,620 --> 01:21:54,580
And it radiates,

2085
01:21:54,580 --> 01:21:56,540
and it radiates away its energy.

2086
01:21:56,800 --> 01:21:59,020
As it radiates away its energy,

2087
01:21:59,280 --> 01:22:00,260
it shrinks,

2088
01:22:00,400 --> 01:22:02,240
and what happens to its energy...

2089
01:22:02,240 --> 01:22:03,940
What happens to its temperature?

2090
01:22:07,460 --> 01:22:08,360
Temperature goes up.

2091
01:22:10,520 --> 01:22:12,900
As the star runs out of fuel,

2092
01:22:13,220 --> 01:22:14,300
it heats up.

2093
01:22:15,380 --> 01:22:16,940
Its temperature goes up.

2094
01:22:17,660 --> 01:22:19,240
What happens is...

2095
01:22:19,240 --> 01:22:20,640
Let me give you an example,

2096
01:22:20,640 --> 01:22:21,040
first of all.

2097
01:22:21,540 --> 01:22:24,640
Just a planet orbiting the sun.

2098
01:22:24,840 --> 01:22:26,180
Suppose there's a little bit of friction.

2099
01:22:26,580 --> 01:22:27,920
A little bit of friction,

2100
01:22:28,080 --> 01:22:30,480
or it radiates away energy

2101
01:22:30,480 --> 01:22:32,200
in the form of gravitational waves,

2102
01:22:32,260 --> 01:22:34,700
anything which decreases the energy of the planet

2103
01:22:34,700 --> 01:22:35,500
as it goes around.

2104
01:22:35,820 --> 01:22:37,620
It starts to orbit inward,

2105
01:22:37,860 --> 01:22:39,600
and it loses its energy

2106
01:22:39,600 --> 01:22:42,400
by increasing its negative gravitational energy.

2107
01:22:42,940 --> 01:22:44,320
Its energy increases

2108
01:22:44,320 --> 01:22:47,640
because its gravitational energy goes up,

2109
01:22:47,640 --> 01:22:49,120
but its gravitational energy is negative.

2110
01:22:49,220 --> 01:22:50,580
So it spirals in,

2111
01:22:50,580 --> 01:22:52,000
losing its energy,

2112
01:22:52,200 --> 01:22:54,780
but what happens to the velocity as it spirals in?

2113
01:22:55,300 --> 01:22:56,860
The answer is it goes up.

2114
01:22:57,260 --> 01:23:01,540
It loses more potential energy

2115
01:23:01,540 --> 01:23:03,740
than it gains kinetic energy

2116
01:23:04,400 --> 01:23:05,400
by a factor of two.

2117
01:23:05,760 --> 01:23:07,420
So as it spirals in,

2118
01:23:07,540 --> 01:23:08,720
it loses energy,

2119
01:23:08,720 --> 01:23:09,680
but it speeds up.

2120
01:23:09,860 --> 01:23:11,680
And because it speeds up,

2121
01:23:11,820 --> 01:23:13,880
if these were individual molecules

2122
01:23:14,519 --> 01:23:17,540
falling into the gravitating object,

2123
01:23:17,840 --> 01:23:20,100
it would mean that its temperature goes up.

2124
01:23:20,580 --> 01:23:22,460
So this is an odd situation,

2125
01:23:22,460 --> 01:23:22,940
alright,

2126
01:23:23,080 --> 01:23:24,420
but it's not all that uncommon,

2127
01:23:25,179 --> 01:23:28,880
that the temperature increases

2128
01:23:28,880 --> 01:23:31,220
as the energy decreases.

2129
01:23:31,780 --> 01:23:33,500
The smaller the black hole,

2130
01:23:33,660 --> 01:23:34,640
the higher the temperature.

2131
01:23:35,280 --> 01:23:36,840
The smaller the energy,

2132
01:23:36,980 --> 01:23:38,100
the higher the temperature.

2133
01:23:38,640 --> 01:23:40,880
The bigger the black hole,

2134
01:23:40,980 --> 01:23:42,060
the lower the temperature.

2135
01:23:43,540 --> 01:23:46,640
So a black hole of stellar mass,

2136
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:48,560
a black hole of...

2137
01:23:51,459 --> 01:23:53,400
mass of one solar mass,

2138
01:23:53,740 --> 01:23:55,360
has a temperature of something like

2139
01:23:55,360 --> 01:23:57,180
about 10 to the minus eighth degrees Kelvin.

2140
01:23:59,319 --> 01:24:02,480
The temperature is inversely proportional to the mass,

2141
01:24:02,740 --> 01:24:05,160
so a black hole at the center of the galaxy

2142
01:24:05,160 --> 01:24:08,540
with a mass a million times bigger

2143
01:24:08,540 --> 01:24:09,600
or a billion times bigger

2144
01:24:09,600 --> 01:24:11,540
would have a temperature a billion times smaller.

2145
01:24:12,660 --> 01:24:13,380
Of course,

2146
01:24:13,380 --> 01:24:14,260
there are other reasons

2147
01:24:14,260 --> 01:24:15,960
why black holes have temperature.

2148
01:24:16,540 --> 01:24:19,200
Having nothing whatever to do with quantum mechanics

2149
01:24:19,200 --> 01:24:21,520
and Hawking and Bekenstein and all of that,

2150
01:24:22,140 --> 01:24:23,360
they may have temperature,

2151
01:24:24,300 --> 01:24:25,060
observational temperature,

2152
01:24:25,220 --> 01:24:26,420
for a totally different reason.

2153
01:24:27,020 --> 01:24:27,500
Namely,

2154
01:24:27,500 --> 01:24:29,740
there may be gas swirling around them,

2155
01:24:29,800 --> 01:24:31,600
and as the gas swirls around them,

2156
01:24:31,620 --> 01:24:32,160
it heats,

2157
01:24:32,260 --> 01:24:33,340
and as it heats,

2158
01:24:33,340 --> 01:24:34,100
it gives off light,

2159
01:24:34,280 --> 01:24:35,830
but eventually that gas will

2160
01:24:35,830 --> 01:24:37,380
be absorbed by the black hole,

2161
01:24:37,900 --> 01:24:40,420
and when the black hole is in an environment

2162
01:24:41,940 --> 01:24:43,740
which is otherwise empty space,

2163
01:24:44,120 --> 01:24:45,480
it has a temperature,

2164
01:24:45,620 --> 01:24:48,380
and the temperature is inverse to its mass.

2165
01:24:49,200 --> 01:24:50,260
So that's the application

2166
01:24:50,260 --> 01:24:52,600
of some of the thermodynamic relationships

2167
01:24:52,960 --> 01:24:54,660
and some of the ideas of information,

2168
01:24:55,639 --> 01:24:56,200
energy,

2169
01:24:57,559 --> 01:24:58,120
entropy,

2170
01:24:59,099 --> 01:24:59,660
temperature,

2171
01:25:00,440 --> 01:25:02,200
and how they fit together

2172
01:25:02,200 --> 01:25:04,860
in a surprising way

2173
01:25:04,860 --> 01:25:06,380
in a black hole.

2174
